      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "61985412ad768d69",
        "text": "My intention in this hour is first of all to point out this development and to mark its limits, in order to then try with a new approach to formulate individual points of view of a kind of second generation, a \"second order cybernetics\", a \"theory of observing systems\" and the like. So first of all to the starting points. One development lay in the metaphor or models that worked with the concept of equilibrium. This had first of all a mathematical basis insofar as one tried to work with mathematical functions, but metaphor is also interesting independently of that and, incidentally, one of the oldest sources of systemic thinking, in use long before the word \"system\" was given a certain prominence, long, of course, before one could speak of \"systems theory\" in the true meaning. I don't know exactly when it started, but the equilibrium metaphor is already in use as a matter of course in the 17th century in the idea of the \"balance of trade\", motivates towards the end of the century also the idea of an international, especially a European balance of nations (or political factors), and finds beyond that a general and relatively indefinite use."
