    {
      "type": "edit",
      "id": "bd02bf15eba5c249",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "bd02bf15eba5c249",
        "text": "Looking back on this development, we can say that it can be characterized by a distinction, namely the distinction between a stable state and a disturbance. Normally, the accent is placed on stability. An equilibrium is thought of as stable, responding only to disturbances, and responding in such a way that either the old equilibrium is restored or a new state of equilibrium is reached. The metaphor presupposes some mechanics, some implementation, some infrastructure that ensures that equilibrium is maintained. From there, the idea that equilibrium theories are stability theories is dominant. However, if you look more closely, and there are such hints as early as the 17th century, this becomes questionable. If one is guided by the idea of a balance, a state of equilibrium of two scales, it immediately becomes clear that this equilibrium is extraordinarily easy to disturb. One need only add a small weight to one of the scales, and the balance is debalanced."
      },
      "date": 1678116774071
    },
    {
      "item": {
        "type": "factory",
        "id": "feee15ea87c9eb52"
      },
      "id": "feee15ea87c9eb52",
      "type": "add",
      "after": "bd02bf15eba5c249",
      "date": 1678116845854
    },
    {
      "type": "edit",
      "id": "feee15ea87c9eb52",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "feee15ea87c9eb52",
        "text": "That is, the idea of equilibrium can be thought of as a theory that designates and also localizes the susceptibility of a system to disturbance - you know what to do if you want to disturb the equilibrium. From a point of view that will come up again and again in the lecture, this theory is a theory of a specific distinction rather than a theory of a desirable state or a particular kind of object. The concept of equilibrium contains a theory that has interest in seeing how the relation of disturbance and stability can be ordered. Perhaps one can even say, but this goes beyond the literature, that it has an interest in seeing how the ratio of perturbation to stability can be increased so that a system is still stable despite being highly perturbable. If you project that to mathematics, the interest turns to the question of what mathematical equations can be used to read such a ratio. Nevertheless, this moment of perturbation has been seen repeatedly in the tradition and also in the more recent use of equilibrium theories, but the accent has clearly been on stability. As if keeping a system stable is a value, and as if the institutions that guarantee equilibrium must strive to keep the system stable. This is especially true of economic theory, of the notion of economic equilibrium, of a balance of various economic factors. Here, doubts have also set in as to whether one can speak of equilibrium as a stable state at all, if one includes reality, if one does not only have mathematical functions in mind, but imagines how real systems, such as economic systems, such as production systems, can be stable."
      },
      "date": 1678116848376
    },
    {
      "item": {
        "type": "factory",
        "id": "0480d72de4c7ec39"
      },
      "id": "0480d72de4c7ec39",
      "type": "add",
      "after": "feee15ea87c9eb52",
      "date": 1678116943411
    },
    {
      "type": "edit",
      "id": "0480d72de4c7ec39",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "0480d72de4c7ec39",
        "text": "From there it has come to considerations whether just the other way round imbalance could not be a condition of stability. According to this, an economic system could only be stable if it either produces too many goods in order to be able to offer something in any case when there is a demand on the market, or if, conversely, it produces too many buyers and too few goods in order to have buyers in any case who, if enough goods are available, will buy them. Jänos Kornai, a Hungarian economist, has developed such anti-equilibrium concepts.2 One can see that this maps respectively the Western and Eastern economies within the capitalist-socialist controversy: Either goods must be kept scarce and buyers or demand abundant, then you are in the socialist system, or conversely buyers must be scarce and goods abundant, then you are in the capitalist system. In any case, we are dealing here with a version of nonequilibrium theory that differs from classical and neoclassical economics in that it moves stability from equilibrium to disequilibrium."
      },
      "date": 1678116945086
    },
