        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "0ed3873839928594",
        "text": "The equilibrium model, at any rate, establishes a strand of developments toward a general systems theory. However, this was not a new discovery in the 1950s, but only a variant to which one could fall back if necessary. New were two other sets of problems, which then influenced the further development of systems theory more strongly than this equilibrium theory. New was above all the question, coming from thermodynamics, how systems can be preserved at all, if one has to assume that physics, at least the physics of closed systems, tends to generate entropy, i.e. to dissolve all distinctions, to bring about a distinctionless state or, physically speaking, to bring about a state in which there is no more usable energy, i.e. no energy that can generate any distinctions. If this is a general physical law, how is it possible to explain the facts of the physical, chemical, biological, social world at all? How is it possible to explain that there is order and that, limiting the perspective to a few billion years, one cannot see that such a development towards entropy is actually taking place? In other words, how is negentropy to be explained as a deviation from the state of entropy, when the laws of physics in themselves run toward entropy? In this question one had in mind that the entropy laws presuppose a closed system, and one imagined, for example, the world as a closed system into which nothing enters from the outside and from which nothing can be led out from the inside."
      },
      "date": 1678117230801
    },
    {
      "type": "add",
      "id": "340b3567aecef21a",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "340b3567aecef21a",
        "text": "⇒ [[Negentropy]]"
      },
      "after": "0ed3873839928594",
      "date": 1678117320291
    },
    {
      "id": "0ed3873839928594",
      "type": "remove",
      "removedTo": {
        "page": "Negentropy"
      },
      "date": 1678117507829
    },
    {
      "type": "add",
      "id": "5f32d5ae16416c3e",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "5f32d5ae16416c3e",
        "text": "This model may have its validity as a world model, but it is inapplicable for all relations within the world. It is the model of a closed system, and such systems are not found in the world, at least not when it comes to living systems, to mental and social systems, that is, at least not when we consider the area that interests us in this lecture. Therefore, the idea of closed systems was negated for the field of biology and sociology and instead a theory of open systems was developed: open systems because one wanted to explain why entropy does not occur and why order is established. Now openness means in any case exchange with the environment, but depending on whether one thinks of biological or organic systems or of sense-oriented systems, i.e. of social systems (communication systems) and of mental systems (consciousness and the like), this idea of exchange takes different forms. For biological systems, one thinks primarily of energy input and output of useless energy; for sense systems, one thinks primarily of exchange of information. A sense system draws information from its environment, interprets, if we may say so, surprises, and is built into a network of other systems that responds to this information-processing system. The basic condition that explains entropy is the same in both cases, namely exchange relations between system and environment. This is what the term open system refers to."
      },
      "after": "340b3567aecef21a",
      "date": 1678117697964
    },
